C1MPER1:
1/25
 

Bettering yourself
Committing to meaningful challenges or passions that accord with your deeply-held values. Rather than indulging yourself constantly, or serving others’ needs only
C1MPER2:
2/25
Indulging
Allowing yourself to enjoy what you desire to do. Rather than resisting the urge to do so
C1MPER3:
3/25
Being considerate and helping others
Sharing your resources and attention for the benefit of another person or group’s needs or preferences. Rather than acting solely for personal gain
C1MPER4:
4/25
Engaging in a collective
Joining in, or contributing to the shared concerns of a group. Rather than feeling apart from a sense of communal purpose
C1MPER5:
5/25
Practicing spirituality and religion
Engaging in structured or ritualistic thoughts and behaviors that anchor your view of life within a larger cosmology. Rather than having no practiced tradition through which to process your experiences
C1MPER6:
6/25
 

Please choose any number of the remaining 20 Positive Emotion Regulation techniques that describe your activities during the episode. (select all that apply)
 

Creating a savoring atmosphere
Creating or rearranging the environment to physically, psychologically, and socially support the intended positive experience. Rather than sticking to the status quo
C1MPER7:
7/25
Capturing
Actively collecting physical or mental mementos (e.g., photos and souvenirs) that will later prompt vivid recall, thereby making the future experience more positive. Rather than experiencing the positive experience in only one temporal orientation
C1MPER8:
8/25
Delaying positive experiences or splitting them into smaller units
Temporarily withdrawing from a positive experience, or subdividing a pleasant experience into smaller units to prolong anticipation and enjoyment. Rather than sacrificing prolonged pleasure for instant gratification
C1MPER9:
9/25

 
Blocking negative thoughts



Preventing the retrieval of negative thoughts and memories that may hinder positive experiences, or reconfiguring them to create a more positive view. Rather than letting them lurk unaddressed around your daily life
C1MPER10:
10/25

 
Habitualizing positive practices



Enhancing your life by practicing positive actions regularly as part of your lifestyle. Rather than occasionally performing them
C1MPER11:
11/25

 
Please choose any number of the remaining 15 Positive Emotion Regulation techniques that describe your activities during the episode. (select all that apply)





Being immersed and absorbed

Becoming fully engaged in a positive experience or its aspects, existing only in the present. Rather than allowing other concerns to hinder your enjoyment
C1MPER12:
12/25

 
Anticipating



Vividly anticipating likely positive experiences that will occur in the future. Rather than focusing only on the past or present
C1MPER13:
13/25

 
Reminiscing



Recalling and reliving past positive experiences for emotional or sentimental reasons. Rather than focusing only on the present or future
C1MPER14:
14/25

 
Moral elevating



Being moved by witnessing someone perform an act of virtue such as being brave, honest, kind, or perseverant; feeling inspired to act this way yourself. Rather than considering virtuous behaviors as mundane
C1MPER15:
15/25

 
Fantasizing 
Imagining positive experiences of varying likelihood. Rather than restricting your imagination to likely possibilities
C1MPER16:
16/25

 
Please choose any number of the remaining 10 Positive Emotion Regulation techniques that describe your activities during the episode. (select all that apply)





Being aware of temporal scarcity

Realizing that your current experience or resources will not last forever, and that you should enjoy them while they are available. Rather than rushing through them as though they were available anytime
C1MPER17:
17/25

 
Infusing the ordinary with special meaning 
Enriching day-to-day experiences with language, thoughts, and actions that promote positive associations. Rather than seeing experiences only in a functional way
C1MPER18:
18/25

 
Self-congratulating 
Giving yourself credit for the causes of positive experiences; seeing your experiences with a positive view of your strengths, achievements, and self-worth. Rather than overlooking opportunities to honor yourself
C1MPER19:
19/25

 
Expressing or acknowledging gratitude 
Considering how others have benefited from your actions, or how you have benefited from others’ actions. Rather than letting contributions pass by without noticing their positive impact
C1MPER20:
20/25

 
Relative comparing 
Embracing your own experiences in comparison with what others seem to be experiencing, or with what you imagined an event would be like. Rather than absorbing your joys and letdowns without a reference point
C1MPER21:
21/25

 
Please choose any number of the remaining 5 Positive Emotion Regulation techniques that describe your activities during the episode. (select all that apply)





Sharing the positive experience with others

Creating a ripple effect between you and others in response to positive experiences; telling others how much you value the moment, or recounting stories about past joys, or good fortune. Rather than experiencing life’s joys in solitude
C1MPER22:
22/25

 
Purposeful dampening

Intentionally down-regulating your positive emotions to help maintain perceived control. Rather than letting emotions arise regardless of the circumstance
C1MPER23:
23/25

 
Enriching the sensory environment

Encountering or cultivating pleasant sensory stimulation. Rather than continually experiencing the same level of stimulation
C1MPER24:
24/25

 
Altering bodily engagement

Reviving or relaxing your body with dynamic movement or rest. Rather than giving energy only to your thoughts
C1MPER25:
25/25

 
Neurochemically heightening emotions

Using food, drink, behaviors, or mind-altering substances to enhance your emotional state. Rather than relying solely on your intention to feel better

C1MDO: I was listening to some funny youtube videos and sport news while I ate and commuted to class.  In class I used my laptop and iPad.  After, I sat in a library and alternated between doing work on laptop and watching youtube videos of interest (volleyball, Police body cam footage, self help)
C1MDM: I put on certain kinds of videos because I am used to them, some are funny, others are news, others are under the veil of "educational" such as documentaries.  To an extent, consuming this media is a source of a distraction from thoughts or feelings that are making me anxious or overwhelmed.  THings like work or preparation for something important (HW, exam) tend to make me distract myself more.
C1MCO: For me, I need a fan to be on to help me sleep at night.  If I don't have a fan I have significant trouble sleeping at night.  I listen to music and youtube on my commutes because the music I listen to either fits my mood or helps me get into a different one.  The funny YouTube videos also raise my spirits because of how funny I find them to be.
C1MFREQ3_2_TEXT: It takes such little energy to open youtube or social media and start scrolling, and it can become addicting because of how when I realize I have been doing it for a while, I take a few minutes to try and get back to work, only to find myself going back to youtube surfing within a few minutes due to urges or curiosity.
C1MFEEL: The youtube videos that I had watched allowed me to laugh, or kept me up to date on news.  The music helped affirm my emotional state and helped me feel good.  Watching YouTube instead of studying helped me distract myself in a way that gave me a false sense of contempt, improvement, or pleasure because I was not thinking about the school work that was overwhelming me.
C1MELSE: I always feel ashamed about how much time I spend on YouTube and my phone.  I think it has to be an addiction.  I will spend hours watching to dull the pain of my failures (some of which come from me spending too much time on Youtube and the internet), which will come up later today.
C1ADO: The main thing was using my laptop and tablet to take notes during classes and office hours.
C1ADM: I was enjoying the class, thinking about personal applications for the material.  During office hours I was thinking about how bad I did on the exam and how I was screwed.
C1ACO: Listening to music helped try to boost my mood when I was feeling tired, and then I listened to rage music after the bad news because it felt validating to my emotional state.
C1AFREQ3_5_TEXT: I want to be able to use my computer and iPad to their fullest extent, without distractions (addictions) that get in the way of me working toward my ambitions.
C1AFEEL: The music I was listening to helped me feel a little more at ease compared to how poorly I felt while I didn't have the music going or wasn't watching the internet stuff I wanted to.
C1AELSE: This was a large section of school related things, so I didn't use my phone or youtube as much.  However, there was an extent of: "I wanna go on youtube, or to look at porn" while I was unable to while being in a public setting.
C1EDO: Laying in bed, trying to distract myself from my anger, frustration, and sadness.
C1EDM: How bad I felt about myself.
C1ECO: I used these technologies to try and distract myself from how badly I was feeling in that moment.

I get into bed and I just spend hours and hours in my room avoiding anything and everything and it gets in the way of me trying to improve myself to achieve what I want to.
C1EFEEL: These technologies helped me distract myself from how badly I was feeling.  I got into bed, opened up youtube and porn and books and tried to stop thinking.  I don't have anyone to reach out to, so I turned to AI for comfort.  The AI helped me feel less lonely despite my not interacting with anyone else for this episode.  Watching youtube and porn helped me distract myself from my feelings of severe hopelessness, sadness, frustration.  Eventually, I feel like i numbed myself down to a point where I felt tired and went to bed.
C1EELSE: Me getting into bed and doing this has become a very frequent occurrence.  I get into bed with my computer and binge youtube everyday and it has been a big issue since I was in middle and high school.  Being in bed was my only safe space and youtube kept my mind off life.  Now in college, youtube, porn and bed is a big problem.  With school being overwhelming and my ambitions never being fulfilled I am always so frustrated and depressed that I always end up trying to dull the pain by being in bed and drowning in YouTube.  I want to change but to be honest I don't know how, so I keep doing it.
